uglas, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Of, Douglas":"Douglas, Kaapprovinsie, Zuid-Afrika","Douglas Castle, Lanackshire, Scotland":"Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","London, England":"London, England"},"en":{"about 1230–12 October 1297":"about 1230–12 October 1297","1240–Female":"1240–Deceased","1265–Male":"1265–Deceased","1276–Female":"1276–Deceased","1280–1350":"1280–1350","1292–Male":"1292–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1230–1297":"1230–1297","1297":"1297","1230":"1230","1350":"1350","1240":"1240","12 October 1297":"12 October 1297","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","ABT 1265":"about 1265","Abt 1276":"about 1276","1276":"1276","1265":"1265","Abt 1292":"about 1292","about 1230":"about 1230","Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Douglas Castle, Douglas, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Of, Douglas":"Douglas, Cape Province, South Africa","Douglas Castle, Lanackshire, Scotland":"Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Douglas","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from any of various places called from their situation on a river named with Gaelic <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black’ + <i>glas</i> ‘stream’ (a derivative of <i>glas</i> ‘blue’). There are several localities in Scotland and Ireland so named, but the one from which the surname is derived in most if not all cases is Douglas in Lanarkshire 20 miles south of Glasgow, the original stronghold of the influential Douglas family and their retainers.","History: The family taking their name from Douglas in Lanarkshire were of Flemish origin. They rose to great prominence in the 14th and 15th centuries, controlling the earldoms of Douglas, Morton, and Angus, and later, Queensberry."],"variants":[{"name":"Douglass","meanings":["Scottish and English (Durham and Northumbria): variant of   Douglas  .","History: William Douglass, a physician recognized for his identification and description of an epidemic of scarlet fever, was born <i>c.</i> 1691 in Gifford, Haddington County, Scotland, and settled in Boston in 1718. The abolitionist, orator, and journalist Frederick Douglass assumed the name after escaping from slavery in 1838 and traveling to Massachusetts. Son of a white father and a slave with some Indian blood, he was born Frederick Augustus Washington Bailey <i>c.</i> 1817 in Tuckahoe, MD."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"'Le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Profit’ or ‘sharp’.","2  ♀, ♂ ‘Upright’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hardi'","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: transferred use of the surname, in origin a nickname for a brave or stout‐hearted man (from Middle English, Old French <i>hardi</i>, of Germanic origin)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":60,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William 'Le Hardi' of Douglas was born about 1230, in Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Scotland. He had at least 3 sons and 2 daughters with Lady Douglas. He died on 12 October 1297, in London, England, at the age of 68."},"et":{"about 1230–12 October 1297":"umbes 1230–12. oktoober 1297","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1276–Female":"1276–Surnud","1280–1350":"1280–1350","1292–Male":"1292–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1230–1297":"1230–1297","1297":"1297","1230":"1230","1350":"1350","1240":"1240","12 October 1297":"12. oktoober 1297","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","ABT 1265":"umbes 1265","Abt 1276":"umbes 1276","1276":"1276","1265":"1265","Abt 1292":"umbes 1292","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Douglas Castle, Douglas, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Of, Doug